{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Why it matters when the Civil War actually ended.", "abstract": "Op-Ed article by historian Gregory P Downs examines mythology that Civil War ended with battle of Appomattox; argues that by separating battlefield events from complexities of Reconstruction that followed, Civil War becomes meaningless feud ending in regional reconstruction; holds that truly understanding the problems of governance created by war is lesson that such mythologies dangerously bury from sight, dooming nation's leaders, and voters, to continually repeat history.", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "12", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "DOWNS", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Gregory", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "P."}], "original": "By GREGORY P. DOWNS", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/12/opinion/sunday/the-dangerous-myth-of-appomattox.html", "lead_paragraph": "Why it matters when the Civil War actually ended.", "headline": {"print_headline": "The Dangerous Myth of Appomattox", "main": "The Dangerous Myth of Appomattox", "content_kicker": "Opinion", "kicker": "Opinion"}, "_id": "5529683338f0d81a55c4e925", "word_count": "1085", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/04/12/sunday-review/12Appomattox/12Appomattox-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/04/12/sunday-review/12Appomattox/12Appomattox-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2015/04/12/sunday-review/12Appomattox/12Appomattox-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/04/12/sunday-review/12Appomattox/12Appomattox-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "400"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/04/12/sunday-review/12Appomattox/12Appomattox-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2015/04/12/sunday-re